args: Our village will no longer need to send\nyoung people to their deaths ever again.\nI don't know how to thank you!
You don't need to thank us at all.
Slaying fiends who threaten\nthe innocent is our duty.
Be that as it may, I still wish to do\nSOMETHING to repay you.
I know! Why not take that dress?!
We are a poor village, and have nothing\nelse that might serve as a fitting reward.

The village weaver always worked hard to
make the finest dresses around, believing
it the least we could do for the poor girls.
It's frankly our most valuable possession.
You can keep or sell it as you see fit.
But please, young Paladyn,\nwon't you accept it?
It would be difficult for Elisanne to accept\nit given her position—and I'm unsure what\nshe would do with it regardless.
Hmm? Why do you look so surprised?
You ain't plannin' to get hitched, are ya?
But wearing this bespoke dress has given\nme an appreciation for just how beautiful\nand lovingly made it is.
I can tell the village weaver poured\neverything into it.
How could I turn away such a gift\nwithout grave insult?
That is why I intend to give it\na fine home in the castle.
All this time, I've been convinced that\nI needed to dedicate myself entirely to\nmy duties as a Paladyn.
But that was just a tale I told myself.
Continuing to devote myself entirely\nto my work is, of course, an option.
But I can also choose to get married\nAND continue my duties as a Paladyn.
I might even start a family someday.
Ah, but this is folly. Why think about such\nthings when I don't even have a partner?
I have no idea when the day will come\nthat I wear a wedding dress for real.\nMaybe it will NEVER come.
But right now, I have something to fight\nfor—so I will continue to give that my all.
Still, I suppose there's no harm in\ndreaming about future possibilities?
Thank you for listening to me, Matilda.
Do you have a moment, Elly?
Your Highness? Yes, of course!\nI'm coming!
A merchant from town just dropped\nthis book off for you.
It's called ＂Perfect Weddings for Blushing\nBrides.＂ Apparently you ordered it?
(I SPECIFICALLY told that merchant to\nwrap this in MANY layers of thick paper!)
(Ah, and what ill luck for His Highness\nto be the one to deliver it!)
I never thought of you as someone\nwho would read these kinds of books.
I...I merely wish to learn more\nabout this aspect of society!

Paladyns fight to protect people's
happiness, and we can't do so without
knowing what their happiness IS.
Yes, that's it...
Through this ordeal, Elisanne learned that\nmarriage wasn't out of reach for her after all.
But alas, the day she learns to be honest about\nher own feelings seems far off indeed...
